Spen.) The explanation given is that Crito is supposed to hesitare, and Pamphilus, afraid that ho has forgotten the name, thinks that this means ruin for himself. But even Pamphilus does not know how much significance lies in the name, and therefore is not likely to cry out peril because of a slight forgetfulness on Crito's part. We may well believe, too, that Pamphilus himself could easily supply the name, if it were essential, for he must often have heard it from Glycerium.
